				<h3>Overview</h3>
				<p>After the successful launch of Cakeâ€™s <a href="https://www.joincake.com/online-memorial-pages/" target="_blank">Memorial page creation service</a>, the next challenge was tackling one of the biggest pain of Cake users -- paying for it.</p>

				<p>Typically when it came to raising money, people would rely on services like GoFundMe. However, making the user leave the site created a disjointed experience and risked them never coming back.</p>



				
				<h3>Team & Role</h3>
				<p>I served as a <strong>UX Designer</strong> and <strong>Front End Developer</strong>. The team included two Back End Developers, one Front End Developer and a Project Manager. My main tasks included:</p>
				
				<p>
					<ul>
						<li>sketching</li>
						<li>wireframing</li>
						<li>user flows</li>
						<li>qualitative research (exit surveys, screen recordings, heat maps)</li>
						<li>quantitative research (conversion data, clickthrough rate)</li>
						<li>competitor analysis</li>
					</ul>
				</p>

				<p>(Awesome note: Because I had coding alongside this team for years, I was often able to convey quick changes with no need to do redo the design!)</p>

				<h3>Objectives</h3>
				<ul>
					<li>Provide memorial creators with an in-app solution for fundraising</li>
					<li>Give memorial creators a way to share their fundraising story</li>
  					<li>Allow memorial visitors to securely transfer funds from their bank account or credit card</li>			
  				</ul>

				<h3>Target audience</h3>
				<ul>
					<li><strong>Memorial Creator:</strong> The person who created the memorial page, usually a friend or family member of the deceased.</li>
					<li>Users were predominantly within the 30-49 year old range.</li>
					<li>Users had varying levels of tech-savviness, but were generally familiar with making profiles on social media sites like Facebook.</li>	
				</ul>
				<br />


