<h4>Wireframe (Low Fidelity)</h4>
<p>When working on the design, I kept in mind the feelings and emotions that users most often reported as they pertained to funeral planning:</p>
<p>
<ul>
	<li><strong>Fatigue.</strong> People planning a funeral are often tired and may require more breaks to complete a process, sometimes stepping away completely.</li>
	<li><strong>Confusion.</strong> Most people planning a funeral are learning everything for the first time, and can feel confused when presented with unfamiliar terms. (e.g. "columbarium", "direct burial")</li>
	<li><strong>Distrust/wariness.</strong> Unfortunately, many people have experienced identity theft when using Internet services and approach unfamiliar apps with increased caution.</li>
</ul>
</p>
<p>
I wanted to create an experience that felt simple but safe. Grieving users are especially sensitive to being overwhelmed so it was important to guide them at their pace and comfort level.</p>

<p>I made a point of grouping questions in small clusters, with a max of 3-5 fields per screen. This way, the flow allows for pauses, and I could organize questions based on common themes.</p>
<p>Keeping things simple also meant less scrolling, especially for those using mobile devices -- lessening users' cognitive load and risk of abandonment.
</p>

<p>I also recommended adding a Preview option at the end. This feature assures users that they can take a break and come back to finish later. Users had enough on their plate.
</p>

